Here's the recommended approach using a custom `Window` subclass and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom Window class (`AppWindow.cs`):**

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NoteViewModel viewModel) : base(page)
    {
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        _viewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _viewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _viewModel;

    public App(NoteViewModel viewModel)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _viewModel = viewModel;
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell(), _viewModel);
}
```

**3. Restore on first launch too** (in your page or view model):

```csharp
public NoteViewModel()
{
    DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
}
```

### Key things to know

| Point | Why |
|---|---|
| Save in **`OnStopped`** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded |
| Also save in **`OnDestroying`** | Android's back button can skip `Stopped` entirely |
| **Don't** save in `OnDeactivated` | That fires for dialogs/split-screen — the app may never actually background |
| **`OnResumed` doesn't fire on first launch** | Initial sequence is `Created → Activated`, so load the draft in your constructor too |
| Keep handlers **fast** (<1–2 sec) | Android enforces a ~5s ANR timeout; iOS has a background watchdog |

`Preferences` is ideal here since draft text is a small string. For larger state, use `File.WriteAllTextAsync` to app storage instead.
